This takes `rettv` (the caller's value) and copies it INTO the tuple via `tuple_append_tv`. The key is whether this is a shallow or deep copy.

Looking at `tuple_set_item` (line 1438):
```c
*TUPLE_ITEM(tuple, idx) = *tv;
```

This is a shallow copy - it just copies the `typval_T` structure. So if `rettv->v_type == VAR_STRING`, it copies the pointer. Both tuple and rettv now point to the same string data.

Then when error handling at line 1412:
```c
    tuple_free(tuple);
```
This frees the tuple memory, including any string values inside it.

After eval_tuple returns FAIL at line 292, the control flow in eval9_nested_expr just returns `ret` at line 304. And there's no cleanup of rettv. The caller's rettv still contains the copied pointer (to freed data if it was a string/list/tuple).

This is the use-after-free! The outer rettv still contains pointers to freed memory after the inner eval_tuple call fails and frees memory.

